# 7. Fix the cognitive-load problem

## Current weakness

The system currently asks users to think too much.

## Fix

Turn the product into a guided evaluation system.

Instead of asking:
“Which variation is best?”

Ask teams to score on fixed dimensions:

* emotional impact
* coherence
* originality
* audience fit
* production feasibility
* brand alignment, if applicable

Every branch should have:

* summary
* what changed
* why it matters
* likely upside
* likely downside

Now the user does not have to mentally reconstruct everything.

The product should do the structure work.

That means the UI must show:

* baseline version
* changed variable
* resulting shift
* evaluation criteria
* comments by role
* final recommendation trail

This lowers mental friction and increases perceived professionalism.

---

# 8. Fix the no-habit-loop issue

## Current weakness

No reason for users to come back repeatedly.

## Fix

Make the product live inside recurring development cycles.

Habit does not need to be consumer addiction.
B2B habit can be workflow recurrence.

Recurring triggers:

* every new script outline
* every episode development cycle
* every revision meeting
* every adaptation review
* every campaign narrative concept round

You want to become the place where teams go when they ask:

> “Which direction are we actually choosing?”

That is enough for retention in a work product.

To deepen recurrence, add:

* project history
* saved decision rationale
* reusable templates
* performance feedback tied to selected branches
* “last time, branch B outperformed branch A” memory

Now the product accumulates organizational intelligence.

That is sticky.

